			<p>
				I like to make clear in my mind why I'm doing something - when the going gets tough, this is what pulls me back on course.
			</p>

			<p>
			I know exercise is good for me physically(duh) and mentally. It makes me sharper and more productive. I like that aspect of it, but when I don't feel like going and working out, this line of reasoning doesn't move me.
			</p>

			<p class="bold">
			The reason I exercise is to build the mental fortitude to remain consistent in the face of mental and environmental changes.
			</p>

			<p>
			It's an act of defiance -> To practice ignoring how I "feel" right now; I want to do this, so I will. Period.
			</p>

			<p>
			So when I feel like shit some days, and working out is the last thing I want to do, I think of why I'm going. And the "feeling like shit" becomes just another weight to push off of me. And just like any other weight, it becomes easier to lift over time.
			</p>

